Marine researcher and founder of Sea Search, Simon Elwen says panic is unnecessary after two whale carcasses were found in just under a month near Cape Town. Marine researcher and founder of Sea Search, Simon Elwen spoke with eNCA's Dan Moyane about the situation. Courtesy of #DStv403 CAPE TOWN - Two dead whales washed ashore in Cape Town are a harbinger of a growing whale population in the southern hemisphere. That’s the good news from Simon Elwen, founder of Sea Search. The two carcasses washed up in Cape Town over one month. READ: South Africa court halts Shell seismic survey plan in key ruling Elwen said: "It is an indication that we have far higher numbers of whales around our coast and this is happening globally especially in southern hemisphere. "The humpback whale is what we are seeing in the west coastline and Cape Town where the whales has been seen at the moment has been growing in an exponential rate since the end of whaling we rarely seen those numbers kicking in. "In the last few years or so the overall numbers are good news but dead whale is never good news."